{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"574"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/574"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.32,0.45,0.15,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111011"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/574"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41914"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111011"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis resulting in unconscious collapse. His records show a medical history of uncontrolled high alcohol consumption, smoking, ascites, and liver cirrhosis. On examination he has several stigmata of chronic liver disease, including spider naevi, koilonychia and gynaecomastia. He has a distended abdomen with shifting dullness. He is resuscitated and stabilised, and then transferred to the ward following one day of monitoring in the Intensive Care Unit. Some investigations have been performed and his laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110g/L [115-155 g/L]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean Cell Volume: 82fL [80- 100 fL]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 500 x10^9/L [150-450 x10^9/L]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.0 x10^9/L [4.0-10.0 x 10^9/L]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 1.8 [0.9-1.2]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EaPTT: 40 seconds [24-38 seconds]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 55\u00b5mol/L [\u0026lt;20 \u00b5mol/L]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 27 g/L [32- 45 g/L]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen determining his management plan, it is appropriate to categorise the patient\u0027s liver disease and consider his likely overall prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following most accurately reflects his one-year survival rate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["5%","20%","45%","80%","90%"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with haematemesis resulting in an unconscious collapse. This is on a background of probable alcohol-related cirrhosis and the bleed probably being variceal in origin. When managing these patients it is important to put a perspective on the severity of the underlying disease and the expected prognosis. Obviously the more severe the disease, with poorer expectations, treatment may be less aggressive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common scoring system for liver disease is the Child-Pugh classification, which determines a score based on ascites, total bilirubin, albumin, prothrombin time/INR, and encephalopathy. These components of the score can be recalled using the ABCDE acronym, with each parameter assigned 1, 2, or 3 points:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA: \u003C/strong\u003Ealbumin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB: \u003C/strong\u003E(total) bilirubin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC: \u003C/strong\u003Ecoagulation - prothrombin time/INR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED: \u003C/strong\u003Edilation (ascites)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE: \u003C/strong\u003Eencephalopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of 5 to 6 describes grade A (well-compensated) liver disease, a score of 7 to 9 describes grade B (disease with significant functional compromise) liver disease, and a score of 10 to 15 describes grade C (decompensated) liver disease. These classifications provide an estimate of the patient\u0027s 1- and 2-year survival rate. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s bilirubin (total) and albumin levels, plus his INR and the presence of moderate ascites equals a total score of 11 - meaning he has grade C liver disease. A patient with grade C liver disease has a \u003Cstrong\u003E1-year survival of 45%\u003C/strong\u003E and a 2-year survival of 35%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["To determine severity of liver disease, ascites, total bilirubin and albumin levels, INR/ prothrombin time, and encephalopathy can be used within Child- Pugh classification."],"references":["Tsoris A, Marlar CA. Use Of The Child Pugh Score In Liver Disease. [Updated 2021 Mar 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542308/","Sloss A, Kubler P. Prescribing in liver disease. Aust Prescr 2009;32:32-5.https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2009.018"]},"relationships":